It's inspired by Push-E: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1724693 with a simpler way to connect batteries.

The Arduino sketch is still a work in progress but I'll upload it once all the basic functions are complete.

description.text:
This is a small overhead lampshade designed to fully cover the lightbulb while still leaving a good amount of clearance below -- where mine is located, there is a door beneath without enough room for a larger cover.

The lampshade consists of two pieces -- the threads which go on first and are held in place as you screw in the lightbulb, and the lampshade itself which screws onto the threads.

If you over-tighten the lampshade onto its threads, you may have difficulty removing it as the threads can start to spin freely beneath the lightbulb. To fix this, either (1) unscrew the lightbulb along with the lampshade, (2) use a screwdriver to hold the threads in place as you unscrew the lampshade, or (3) use the alternate version of the threads with the grip pattern around the edges.

Obviously, it works best with translucent filament. :)

WARNING: Use only with bulbs that will not get hot! I am currently using it with a small CFL, and the cover gets warm, but not enough to deform or be a fire hazard. Ideally, use an LED bulb.

title: Universal IR Sensor Board Mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This print assumes you know how an IR Sensor Probe works and how one uses it on different surfaces, and have it configured to your printer's needs. I am not liable for any damage done by this print.

This Universal IR Sensor Probe Mount is a board mount meant for this sensor board by MiscSolutions. It has been designed around a Ultimate Greg's Wade's Extruder with a J-Head MK IV-B but can be used on anything with a groove mounting system with tweaking and experimentation.

For the premade STL files, the fixed one is 50mm in length. The adjustable one has a 50mm attachment and a 30mm sensor mount. Assuming the hotend is resting on the bed, you want to get it as close to the bed as you feel comfortable with without it rubbing against the bed. The optimal level is about 1.5 to 2.5 mm away from the bed. This print may curl away from the heat, so a thicker attachment may be needed.

In the default configuration with my hotend, the board starts detecting the bed at about 1.5mm away from it.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Prusa i3

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

1.52mm layers

Infill:

15%

Mounting

To mount it, you simply attach it via the screw for the groovemount holder. Then you attach the sensor board and wala. Make sure that the back of the sensor board faces the extruder, that way there's less chance of damaging the board from heat and flying specs of plastic.

Mistakes were made

I use ABS, and have PET covered glass on a MK3 Heatbed. You need a well painted surface on it to make it detect the glass reliably enough. tl;dr make sure your surface is reliably detectable.

I also ran into the issue of the adjustable one not being very kind. In the end, it turns out that my measurements fit my hotend perfectly, and that's the story of how the fixed one was made.

description.text:
I design this new set of disc brakes for my other traxxas 1/16 e-revo
that i also have as well this is a cosmetic upgrade as you see here
in the photos. If you wish to download this file. The requirements
for these 3-D printed disc brakes you must have the RPM axle carriers
already installed onto your traxxas 1/16 e revo like you see here
in the photos. The photos will give you an idea on how to prepare
them and install them but I will explain to you step-by-step how
to prepare them and to install them.

1 depending upon your 3-D printer you would need to do some sanding
with a dremel or similar power tool to smooth out all of the rough edges.

2 remove the hex nut on the axle carrier and do a test fit to make sure that
everything fits as seen in one of the photos.

3 once the pieces have been sanded out and test fitted then assemble the pads
onto the discs themselves as seen here in one of the photos.

4 then use a little amount of superglue to secure the pads and to the
discs themselves as seen here in one of the photos and let the glue dry.

5 after that then use then hot glue gun then applied a small amount of glue
on the discs themselves not too much because you may have to remove the disc brakes
for maintenance or repairs later. After applying hot glue onto the disk brakes
or axle carriers themselves and quickly install the disgraced themselves and to
the axle carrier before the glue dries.

6 after that the glue is dry test everything out to make sure that the disk brakes
themselves are solid on the axle carrier themselves.

7 after that put the hex nuts themselves back onto the axle carriers then
put the wheels back on and test out the RC vehicle to make sure that they are no
issues in regards to the disk brakes themselves and everything should work out.

description.text:
**Added a V3 and V3.5 version. With the newest PS4 firmware, you can now use external hard drives to store games. I went ahead and bought the Seagate - Backup Plus Slim 4TB external HDD, and found it fits perfectly on one of the wings of the V2 stand. I went ahead and added little rails to each side so that you can rest a HDD on its side there. V3.5 is the same thing but with cut outs in the middle section to hopefully(?) reduce print time. Let me know if these work out for you.

**I added a new V2 version with wider feet. I again made a shorter and a taller version. The feet are about an inch wider on each side than the space where the PS4 occupies, and I have to imagine that's a decent enough amount to keep it from tipping over. especially when using the taller versions. I've left the old versions up in case you trust that amount of support and/or don't want the increased print time. I have not yet printed out the new V2 version yet, so let me know if there is an issue.

Simple stand for the PS4 Pro. Simply took a measurement of how wide the system is (I measured about 54.91 mm), threw this super simple thing together in 3D builder, stuck it in Cura, and then printed. You will need to print at least two of these.

They are not fancy at all, but it seemed to fit nice and snug, and kept the system from wobbling as much as it does normally (which honestly isn't much; it's at least better than the OG PS4 as it's a little bit wider). I made two versions, a taller one that is about 1.8 inches (46.9mm) in height, and a shorter one that is an inch less at .81 inches (20.6mm). To just test it out with a quicker printer, I shrunk the shorter one to 60% its original height in Cura and printed that, and it seems to work even when that small.

I printed the test version at .3mm layer height, with 1.2mm shells, and 25% fill. It took about an hour to print one of the test versions on my Maker Select V2.1.

/After thinking about the design for more than 5 seconds, these (the original designs) are actually probably worse footprint wise than the original console. If I can get some more time, I'll try and come up with something more foolproof. /Added a new version with wider feet.

description.text:
While looking for some wire to solder in oine of my projects, i thought it would be handy, if it was provided from a holder hanging from an IVAR Rack. You see from my projects, that my "office" ( :D ) is filled with IVAR Shelves... So i powered up my newly installed 123D Design Studio (Thanks @ChatToBrian for this great Tip) and built one. It has a hole to pull the cable out as well as a small window to see what color is filled and how much is left. title: Using SCAD primitives to create fillets

description.text:
The primitives provided by the SCAD language, in particular the minkowski() operation, can be used to automatically add fillets to every concave seam of a piece.

However, the operation is expensive and probably not a feasible way to approach things.

This scad file shows a shape made of three interlocking cuboids and a cylinder filleted using a very polygonal sphere. A finer-resolution sphere would produce a far better result, but on my middle-aged macbokk would take hours or more to compute.

comments.author: TBS

comments.text: Well, you can of course represent a 3D model with voxels (raster of 3D pixels), but it is my understanding that stl files store information about the vertices, faces etc. and their relative position, and that amount does not change when scaling up. So the amount of information stored in the file stays the same for whatever scale you are using. Of course the more you scale such a model up, the more you see the triangles of the mesh. But I made the model resolution for the scale of 10x bigger, but accidentally exported it out too small, my bad. But that does not mean that the resolution is therefore inferior, just the scaling of the relative vertex positions is off. Of course I did not mean that stl files are like vector representations which have infinite resolution. Anyway, glad you like it!

description.text:
A printable ball bearing. Very simple.

Best printed with high resolution support (from bed only) using a very fine print resolution, I used 0.06mm layer height and 3000mm/min print speed with 50% underspeed on outlines.

High fill percentage will help too, I had 8 layers top and bottom with 6 perimeter. Basically you want to try and get the balls to print as nicely as possible.

It's reasonably smooth, but it's a 3D printed plastic ball bearing so don't expect it to be anywhere near as smooth as one made from hardened ground steel.

I made this for use in printed assemblies requiring rotational moving parts which were too tightly constrained to use a gear bearing, printed gear bearings are by far the smoothest for 3D printed rotating parts but difficult to print any smaller than about 35mm diameter.

description.text:
I just got my Hero 5 Session and wanted a good way to use it more like a "normal camera" when it isn't attached to my quad copter.

Just a basic gopro connector from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:62800 with a 90 degree handle. I added a foot so it can easily be placed for time lapse or other longer steady shots. Also tossed in a couple of grooves to allow more easy use of a bungee/hairtie/rubber band to hold it. Holes in the grip are for the same purpose.

Notes:

I printed mine in ABS with 3 shells.

I rotated it 90 degrees in my slicer so the foot was down and the handle up for printing.

Support on the bottom of the round edges makes them smoother.

Auto-generated support will fill the entire handle and is a pain to get out. If your slicer allows for customized support I'd only fill the outer holes to keep them round and nice looking or go without if you use active cooling and have your ABS settings really dialed in.

Fixed some missing or duplicate and unused faces, flattend paws so it can be better printed as is with supports (brim still recommended).

It can be printed in two parts, I added cut version also.

description.text:
Here is a turntable set up for spray painting miniatures. It is designed to hold up to 10 miniatures of 30mm diameter or less of larger diameters. The miniatures are stuck to the turntables with blu tack (or equivalent) & the set up allows you to turn each model separately to allow spraying all the way around.

I have added a PDF file with assembly instructions & Set ups.

Summary:
The table can be set up in one of 3 ways

  1. With 10 individual tables of 30mm diameter
  2. With 5 individual tables of 50mm diameter & 5 plugs to protect the holes not used
  3. With 10 plugs to give a flat table

The idea is that you use the large Main Turn Wheel to turn the main Turntable & that will bring your next model to the front to spray it, then you can turn the smaller Sub Turn Wheels to rotate each miniature individually.

The assembly can also be angled upwards through to 30 degrees to allow spraying of them awkward areas beneath overhangs.

comments.text: This is a bit like slamming planes into buildings. Eventually the cat would be out of the bag. I do like this machine and am not one to recommend trying to put the genie back in the bottle. I always (just like the aircraft thing) was aware that probably signatures were being forged on voting ballots by many different kinds of computer controlled machines but this machine lowers the price and convenience  bar to a new level. The upshot is we need to return to "voting booths" where a person with a pulse verifies your signature and do away with the mail in voting schemes around the country (except for rare and very exceptional cases). The second line of defense would be a serial number assigned to each ballot (only you would know it and a file in a machine that could only be opened under court order) that you could double check online to make sure your vote was cast as intended. Not being in any way critical of this machine. I may own one at some point as it has many unique uses but like anything there is a dark side (not the machine but the use) that will need to be addressed at some point. It is time for a change anyway.

description.text: I decided to print out a new higher quality knob for my FT-817 on my replicator. I soon discovered that the model used to print the knob on my cupcake didn't fit right when printed on my new bot with better tolerances. I decided to make my new knob parametric so I could easily make any adjustments in the future. The knew knob is awesome on my radio.

1) Print the knob.
2) Remove the rubber grip ring from your stock FT-817 knob.
3) Remove the set screw fully from the stock knob. You will need a 1.5mm allan key for this.
4) Slide the stock knob straight off and place the new crank knob on.
5) Tighten in the set screw on the side but don't crank it down too tight.
6) Put the rubber grip ring on the new knob. Now you are ready to hook your radio back up and spin the dial for those QSOs.

description.text:
Not being able to find a ballast spreader for use on my O-27 Marx model railroad, I decided to make one myself. It stands about 8.5cm tall X 7.2cm long X 8cm wide (3.25" X 2.75" X 3.13") and should deposit scale ballast at a width of 12 o scale feet.

I had to print it in two parts to accommodate my printer, so I've included the Sketchup file so you can combine the pieces if you so choose.

Updated: I made a single piece version that fits in my printer all in one shot. It's only about 6cm tall now, but it could be edited to be taller. I also ran this one through Blender's mesh check and that fixed the problems the other pieces had. I didn't have any trouble when I printed it out, but this should be water tight now. I'll leave the halfed version, as well, for anyone that wants it.

Another Update: Removed the STL files for the two halfs of the spreader, but I left the sketchup file for it for anyone who wants it. Also added another thing - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1905815 - a roadbed scribe that will slide over the rails in the same way the spreader does. Holds two pencils, or pens, on either side and marks a 12' wide roadbed with the track centred.

Printer:

M3D Micro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

200 microns

Infill:

Low

I printed both the two piece spreader and the one piece to test them. I much prefer the single piece one, it seems sturdier. I included photos of it being used and I am very happy with the result. It is so much more convenient than spooning ballast material on and shaping it with a brush. I used some rather fine dirt in my test and still got a very nice shape.

I added files for a single set, and for 6 sets.

After printing, check the holes on the back and drill out if needed.
Then solder two very thin wires to an SMD LED (I used coil wire from a discarded motor, very thin and insulated by a thin layer of laquer, and 0508 SMD LED's). Wire the leads through the holes and glue the LED in place, nicely centered. Plug the holes with little drops of CA glue, place the floodlights such that they face UP and fill with a couple drops of clear casting resin - or device up an alternative way to make up the "glass" such as gluing a piece of transparent foil over the front.

Then snap the flootlight in its bracket and glue the assembly to your model or diorama.
When you connect the LED, make sure you use an appropriate resistor or LED driver or else your LED will burn out in seconds...

Happy building!

title: Kossel E3D part cooling with IR

description.text:
Part cooling fan and hotend cooling for Kossel. Inspired by many similar designs, but made with size, weight, strength, and suitability to hold the hotend rigid in mind.

Mounting holds for DC42's differential IR sensor (use E3D's heater block sock to insulate the block from the pcb). The PCB mounts inside near the nozzle. Between the air gap and the insulator, the temperature seems to be reasonable for the sensor.

Uses 35mm fans (3510). 40mm fans were too large (and designs accommodating them tend to hit the belts), and 30mm fans are to small and loud. Hence, I used the less common 35mm fan.

I mount this on a metal effector (not the robotdigg one, the other common one you'll find). The mounting holes are at 25mm Diameter. There are recessed holders on 3 holes for nuts so that the entire thing is secured by more than just self-threaed plastic.

Print upside down for best results.

title: Makergear M2 'Mammoth' Bed Cooler
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
After much trial and error I'm ready to present to you my first revision of my new 'mammoth' cooler for the Makergear M2!!

-- This cooler is printed in 3 parts - main body, tube 1, and tube 2.

-- I used the original makergear fan/hotend connector body to accommodate the main platform for the two 50mm 24v blowers so all credit for that piece goes to makergear. I purchased the 50mm blowers from reprapchampion.com.

-- blowers are wired together and wired into a pigtail cut from the original 50mm cooling fan that comes with the M2.

-- I used black hatchbox ABS @ 240c hotend/ 110c build plate, .2mm resolution, .40 extrusion width, .89 extrusion multiplier. (first time ever using ABS, very happy with the result)

-- Printed directly on build plate's PEI surface with no helpers such as glue or slurry. Adhesion was excellent.

-- Supports not required on the two tubes if printed with rectangular opening side on build plate, supports are required on the main body.

-- Assemble with glue or screws (however you see fit) You just have to attach the blowers and the two tubes to the main body.

PART VERSION HISTORY:

title: Z-Axis shim spacer for 2016 FlashForge Creator Pro (for glass bed, customizable)

description.text:
If you want to install a glass bed on your printer, you need to adjust the height at which the Z endstop is triggered, because the extra thickness of the glass is added to the platform. If you don't do this, you are likely to run out of adjustment length of the levelling springs and be unable to level the plate, or risk breaking the glass.

The easiest way to do this, is to add a shim to the platform at the location of the Z endstop. There are many shims available but I couldn't find any for the 2016 FlashForge Creator Pro which seems to have screws in different places than other models, so here's a remix that fits. Ready-to-use models are available in thicknesses from 2 to 6 mm (0.08 to 0.24 inch).
For those who want to make a custom shim of any thickness between 1 and 10 mm, use the Customizer button!

The shims are designed to slightly clamp themselves between the rods, but if you print them in PLA and often do prints with a hot closed chamber, they may lose their ‘springiness’ over time and become a little wiggly. This is not a problem and does not affect their effectiveness.

It is advisable to make sure the shim is perfectly flat to avoid ‘springiness’ while the Z endstop switch is being pushed, which could reduce accuracy. If the part is noticeably curved after removing it from the platform (which tends to happen a lot with ABS prints), use a hair dryer or hot water to soften it, and carefully bend it in the other direction to make it flatter.

comments.text: Can you print at 0.2mm on the FlashForge Creator Pro? I just purchased one and a lot of what I'm seeing on this site wants 0.1mm or .02mm. I can't go below 0.5mm with FlashPrint. I'm I doing something wrong?
comments.author: DarkIsamu

comments.text:
I don't use FlashPrint, but no slicer program should even allow to print at 0.5mm layers with a 0.4mm nozzle. The maximum sensible layer height for a 0.4mm nozzle is 0.3mm. 0.2 is very common for prints that don't require fine details. I haven't seen many things or makes that were printed at less than 0.1mm. Only SLA printers will usually go below 0.1mm layers.
Are you sure you're not off by a factor 10 somewhere? You can ask your question in the FlashForge group, there certainly are other FlashPrint users who can help you.
